{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617249"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:11:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:11:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16461"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16461"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.19,0,0.3,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66098"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9152"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51555"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5048"},{"type":"tags","id":"5082"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22109"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66098"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old medical student presents to their general practitioner complaining of difficulty staying awake during lectures. They report consuming 6-8 cups of coffee daily to maintain alertness. The student is interested in understanding how caffeine works in the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes caffeine\u0027s primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks adenosine receptors","Enhances dopamine neurotransmission","Increases calcium conductance","Stimulates beta-adrenergic receptors","Blocks cyclic nucleotide breakdown"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECaffeine primarily acts as a competitive antagonist that \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocks adenosine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E in the central nervous system. By preventing adenosine from binding to its receptors, caffeine counteracts the natural sleep-promoting and sedating effects of adenosine signaling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile caffeine\u0027s effects may include increased sympathetic tone, it does not directly bind to or \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulate beta-adrenergic\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ereceptors.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECaffeine does not \u003Cstrong\u003Eblock cyclic nucleotide breakdown\u003C/strong\u003E; phosphodiesterase inhibition only occurs at concentrations much higher than those achieved with normal consumption. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAny effects on dopamine such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eenhanced dopamine neurotransmission\u003C/strong\u003E are secondary to adenosine receptor blockade. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECaffeine does not directly modulate calcium channel function at normal doses and therefore does not act to \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreases calcium conductance. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThrough antagonism of adenosine A1 and A2A receptors, caffeine produces its characteristic effects including increased alertness, enhanced cognitive function, and mild bronchodilation. This blockade leads to increased release of excitatory neurotransmitters and enhanced neural activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Caffeine acts as a competitive antagonist at adenosine receptors in the central nervous system.","Caffeine causes bronchodilation, increased alertness, and enhanced cardiac contractility.","The stimulant effects of caffeine are primarily due to blocking the inhibitory effects of adenosine."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51555"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16461"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51555"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T10:01:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T10:21:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9152"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66098"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0